{"title_page": "A Biography", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Biography\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[John Mellencamp|Johnny Cougar]]\n| cover      = A_biography.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 6, 1978\n| recorded   = 1977\u201378\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Wessex Sound Studios|Wessex Studios]], [[Sarm West Studios|Basing Street Studios]], [[Associated Independent Recording|AIR Studios]], [[London]]\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[heartland rock]]\n| length     = 42:58\n| label      = [[Riva Records|Riva]]\n| producer   = [[John Punter]]\n| prev_title = [[Chestnut Street Incident]]\n| prev_year  = 1976\n| next_title = [[John Cougar (album)|John Cougar]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicBioAlbum\"/>\n|rev2 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/john-mellencamp/albumguide Rolling Stone Album Guide]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''''A Biography''''' is [[John Mellencamp]]'s second released album (third recorded), and last credited to his then-[[stage name]] \"Johnny Cougar.\" Recorded in [[London]], it was released in the U.K. and Australia by [[Riva Records]] on March 6, 1978.\n\nDue to poor sales of Mellencamp's debut album, ''[[Chestnut Street Incident]]'', ''A Biography'' did not receive a U.S. release upon its 1978 debut. Two of its tracks, \"Taxi Dancer\" and the single \"[[I Need a Lover]],\" were also included on his 1979 album ''[[John Cougar (album)|John Cougar]]'', which was released in the U.S.\n\nIn Australia, however, \"[[I Need a Lover]]\" became Top 10 hit, giving Mellencamp his first taste of success. The song would eventually crack the Top 40 in the U.S. in late 1979 when released as a single from his ''[[John Cougar (album)|John Cougar]]'' album. [[AllMusic]] reviewer [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] described \"I Need a Lover\" as Mellencamp's \"first good song.\"<ref name=\"allmusicBioAlbum\">{{cite web\n | url        = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=a-biography-r34027|pure_url=yes}}\n | title      = A Biography \u2013 John Mellencamp\n | work       = [[Allmusic]]\n | accessdate = October 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n''A Biography'', along with all Mellencamp's other Riva Records/Mercury Records albums, were remastered and re-released in 2005, marking the first time ''A Biography'' was released in the United States. \n\nMellencamp has often spoken negatively about his early albums, and ''A Biography'' is no exception. He stated in Tim Holmes\u2019 1986 biography: \u201c''A Biography'' is so bitter. I mean I don\u2019t even like to listen to it. I can\u2019t believe it\u2019s me. The songs were written in \u201976 or \u201977. The lyrics were real awful. They were real \u2018I hate you. I hate this.\u2019 And that\u2019s the way I felt at that time.\"\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Tracklist\n| all_writing = [[John Mellencamp]]\n| headline = Side One\n| title1 = Born Reckless\n| length1 = 4:35\n| title2 = Factory\n| length2 = 3:02\n| title3 = Night Slumming\n| length3 = 4:40\n| title4 = Taxi Dancer\n| length4 = 4:05\n| title5 = [[I Need a Lover]]\n| length5 = 5:37\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Side Two\n| title1 = Alley of the Angels\n| length1 = 3:58\n| title2 = High C Cherrie\n| length2 = 4:58\n| title3 = Where the Sidewalk Ends\n| length3 = 3:56\n| title4 = Let Them Run Your Lives\n| length4 = 5:55\n| title5 = Goodnight\n| length5 = 2:05\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* Johnny Cougar&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[acoustic guitar]], [[background vocals]]\n* Brian BecVar&nbsp;\u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], background vocals\n* [[Larry Crane (guitarist)|Larry Crane]] \u2013 [[guitar]]s, background vocals\n* Robert \"Ferd\" Frank&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]], background vocals\n* Tom Knowles&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum kit|drums]], background vocals\n* [[Andy Mackay]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[saxophone]]s\n* Ann Odell&nbsp;\u2013 [[string instrument|string]] arrangement on \"Taxi Dancer\"\n*[[David Steen (photographer)|David Steen]] \u2013 photography\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{[https://www.itsbiography.com/ John Mellencamp]}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biography, A}}\n[[Category:1978 albums]]\n[[Category:John Mellencamp albums]]\n[[Category:albums produced by John Punter]]\n[[Category:Riva Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Biography\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[John Mellencamp|Johnny Cougar]]\n| cover      = A_biography.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 6, 1978\n| recorded   = 1977\u201378\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Wessex Sound Studios|Wessex Studios]], [[Sarm West Studios|Basing Street Studios]], [[Associated Independent Recording|AIR Studios]], [[London]]\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[heartland rock]]\n| length     = 42:58\n| label      = [[Riva Records|Riva]]\n| producer   = [[John Punter]]\n| prev_title = [[Chestnut Street Incident]]\n| prev_year  = 1976\n| next_title = [[John Cougar (album)|John Cougar]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicBioAlbum\"/>\n|rev2 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/john-mellencamp/albumguide Rolling Stone Album Guide]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''''A Biography''''' is [[John Mellencamp]]'s second released album (third recorded), and last credited to his then-[[stage name]] \"Johnny Cougar.\" Recorded in [[London]], it was released in the U.K. and Australia by [[Riva Records]] on March 6, 1978.\n\nDue to poor sales of Mellencamp's debut album, ''[[Chestnut Street Incident]]'', ''A Biography'' did not receive a U.S. release upon its 1978 debut. Two of its tracks, \"Taxi Dancer\" and the single \"[[I Need a Lover]],\" were also included on his 1979 album ''[[John Cougar (album)|John Cougar]]'', which was released in the U.S.\n\nIn Australia, however, \"[[I Need a Lover]]\" became Top 10 hit, giving Mellencamp his first taste of success. The song would eventually crack the Top 40 in the U.S. in late 1979 when released as a single from his ''[[John Cougar (album)|John Cougar]]'' album. [[AllMusic]] reviewer [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] described \"I Need a Lover\" as Mellencamp's \"first good song.\"<ref name=\"allmusicBioAlbum\">{{cite web\n | url        = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=a-biography-r34027|pure_url=yes}}\n | title      = A Biography \u2013 John Mellencamp\n | work       = [[Allmusic]]\n | accessdate = October 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n''A Biography'', along with all Mellencamp's other Riva Records/Mercury Records albums, were remastered and re-released in 2005, marking the first time ''A Biography'' was released in the United States. \n\nMellencamp has often spoken negatively about his early albums, and ''A Biography'' is no exception. He stated in Tim Holmes\u2019 1986 biography: \u201c''A Biography'' is so bitter. I mean I don\u2019t even like to listen to it. I can\u2019t believe it\u2019s me. The songs were written in \u201976 or \u201977. The lyrics were real awful. They were real \u2018I hate you. I hate this.\u2019 And that\u2019s the way I felt at that time.\"\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Tracklist\n| all_writing = [[John Mellencamp]]\n| headline = Side One\n| title1 = Born Reckless\n| length1 = 4:35\n| title2 = Factory\n| length2 = 3:02\n| title3 = Night Slumming\n| length3 = 4:40\n| title4 = Taxi Dancer\n| length4 = 4:05\n| title5 = [[I Need a Lover]]\n| length5 = 5:37\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Side Two\n| title1 = Alley of the Angels\n| length1 = 3:58\n| title2 = High C Cherrie\n| length2 = 4:58\n| title3 = Where the Sidewalk Ends\n| length3 = 3:56\n| title4 = Let Them Run Your Lives\n| length4 = 5:55\n| title5 = Goodnight\n| length5 = 2:05\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n*