{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani Stadium", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                = Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani\n| nickname            = ''El Fort\u00edn''\n| image               = Argentina A vs Inglaterra A 02.JPG\n| image_size          = 250px\n| caption             = The stadium in 2013 during an [[Argentina national rugby union team]] test match\n| fullname            = Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani\n| former_names        = \n| location            = Avenida Juan B. Justo, 8900, [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]<ref name=cavs>{{cite web |url=http://www.velezsarsfield.com.ar/club/estadio/ |title=Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani |publisher=[[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=5 May 2012 }}</ref>\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|34|38|7.35|S|58|31|14.56|W|type:landmark}}\n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = 1947-51\n| opened              = {{Start date and age|1951|04|22}}\n| renovated           = \n| expanded            = 1978\n| owner               = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]]\n| surface             = Grass\n| scoreboard          = Yes\n| cost                = \n| architect           = \n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 49,540<ref name=cavs/>\n| record_attendance   = \n| dimensions          = 105 x 70 m\n| acreage             = \n| tenants             = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]] (1943\u2013present)<br />[[Jaguares (Super Rugby)|Jaguares]] (2016\u2013present)\n}}\n\nThe '''Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani''' is a [[stadium]] located in the [[Liniers]] neighborhood of [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], near [[Liniers railway station]].<ref name=cavs/> The venue is the home of the [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] club [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]] and is also known as ''El Fort\u00edn de Liniers'' or ''V\u00e9lez Sarsfield''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/venues/argentina/estado-jose-amalfitani/|title=ESTADIO JOS\u00c9 AMALFITANI|work=Soccerway|publisher=Global Sports Media|accessdate=19 November 2012}}</ref> The stadium was named after [[Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani]], who was president of V\u00e9lez Sarsfield for 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/deportes/8-137905-2010-01-02.html |title=Cien a\u00f1os de un club que se hizo grande |author=Daniel Gui\u00f1az\u00fa |newspaper=[[P\u00e1gina/12]] |language=Spanish |date=2010-01-02 |accessdate=2010-10-16 }}</ref>\n\nThe original, temporary stadium was built between 1941 and 1943 in wood, and the current facility was built in cement between 1947 and 1951.<ref name=cavs/> It was renovated and enlarged 26 years later in preparation for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. The stadium has a capacity of 49,540 spectators, although it does not provide seating for all of them like most Argentine stadia.\n\nThe Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani Stadium is also the [[national stadium]] for the [[Argentina national rugby union team]] (''Los Pumas''). Although the team plays test matches throughout the country, their highest-profile tests (such as against the New Zealand All Blacks) are usually held here.\nThe newly formed Argentine [[Super Rugby]] team, [[Jaguares (Super Rugby)|Jaguares]], are playing its home games at the stadium.\n\n==History==\n===First years===\n[[File:Velez1920.png|thumb|right|Grandstands (wooden made) view of the first stadium]]\nDuring its first years of existence, V\u00e9lez Sarsfield football team played its games in vacant lands of the neighborhood, with removable goal posts. In 1913 the [[Argentine Football Association]] ordered the club to host its home games at a bigger stadium so the club moved to the Juan Mart\u00edn Figallo's (a neighbor) countryhouse on Rod\u00f3 and Escalada streets. Figallo rented the club part of his land.\n\nIn 1914, the club called an assembly to discuss the posibility to rent lands on better places. The club got a land behind Villa Luro station, between Cortina and Bacacay streest. But the definitive stadium would be built in 1922, when the club rented a land to L\u00f3pez Bancalari Brothers on Guardia Nacional street. The club started to built a grandstand while the team continued playing in Villa Luro and other fields, until the construction finished. Works were ready in 1924, when the club inaugurated its first stadium with a grandstand, lockers, coffee shop, personnel room and secretary. The stadium was officially opened in a friendly match v [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]].\n\nNew grandstands were built between 1926 and 1927, completing the four sides of the stadium and therefore increasing its capacity. In 1935, the first match with artificial lighting was played at V\u00e9lez Sarsfield venue. The local team defeated [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Platense|Platense]] 4\u20132. The end of an era came in 1940 when the club was intimated to leave the lands where the stadium was located due to the rental contract had expired.\n\n===Current venue===\nAfter suffering [[Promotion and relegation|relegation]] from the [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] in 1940, V\u00e9lez was sacked from the Villa Luro ground they were renting. Three years later, in 1941, the club obtained the terrain of the current stadium, property of the [[Buenos Aires Western Railway]]. The ground was a swamp of the [[Maldonado Stream]], where construction was difficult. However, the club's president [[Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani]] led the construction of the first stadium at the site, which was inaugurated on April 11, 1943. The new stadium used the same wood stands from the old Villa Luro stadium, and was inaugurated in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]. V\u00e9lez striker [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Ferraro]] scored the first goal in the stadium's history (the others were scored by \u00c1ngel Fern\u00e1ndez for V\u00e9lez and [[Adolfo Pedernera]] twice for River). The current stadium was inaugurated on April 22, 1951.\n\nThe stadium was renamed in honor of Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani on December 7, 1968. The following year, a modern lighting system by [[Siemens]] was installed, and the first of the upper stand sections was completed.\n\n==Events hosted==\n=== Football ===\n====1978 FIFA World Cup====\n[[File:Cancha_de_Velez_-_panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|Exterior view of the stadium in 2006]]\n[[File:Velez1.JPG|thumb|right|The stadium at night]]\nThe stadium was refurbished for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]] with the completion of press boxes and another section of upper stands, and hosted three games in the group stages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stadiumguide.com/joseamalfitani/|title=Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani|publisher=The Stadium Guide}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Round\n!Group\n!Team 1\n!Vs.\n!Team 2\n|-\n|June 3 ||1||3||{{fb|AUT}}||'''2\u20131'''||{{fb|ESP|1977}}\n|-\n|June 7 ||1||3||{{fb|AUT}}||'''1\u20130'''||{{fb|SWE}}\n|-\n|June 11 ||1||3||{{fb|ESP|1977}}||'''1\u20130'''||{{fb|SWE}}\n|}\n\n==== Argentina friendly matches ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Date !! Rival !! Res.\n|-\n|  22 April 1974 || {{fb|RUM|1965}} || 2-1 \n|-\n|  5 May 1982 || {{fb|BUL|1971}} || 2-1  \n|-\n|  23 June 1983 || {{fb|CHI}} || 1-0 \n|-\n|  25 September 1984 || {{fb|MEX}} || 1-1  \n|-\n|  16 December 1987 || {{fb|GER}} || 1-0  \n|-\n|  13 March 1991 || {{fb|MEX}} || 0-0 \n|-\n|  27 March 1991 || {{fb|BRA|1968}} || 3-3 \n|-\n|  21 December 1994 || {{fb|RUM}} || 1-0  \n|-\n|  10 March 1998 || {{fb|BUL}} || 2-0 \n|}\n\n=== Rugby union ===\nThe Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani is the current home ground for the [[Jaguares (Super Rugby)|Jaguares]], an Argentine [[Super Rugby]] franchise. The ground has  also hosted the [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina national team]] (''Los Pumas'') since 1986, when the side left to play at [[Estadio Arquitecto Ricardo Etcheverry|Ferro Carril Oeste Stadium]] (their home venue by then) searching for higher capacity stadiums.\n\nWhen [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] played Argentina in November [[2005 South Africa rugby union tour of Argentina and Europe|2005]] at V\u00e9lez Sarsfield, they faced a strong ''Pumas'' side, which took a 20\u201316 lead into the half-time break, before fading in the second half and losing 34\u201323.\n\nIn the [[2006 mid-year rugby test series|2006 mid-year tests]], the second test against [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]], saw the ''Pumas'' win 45\u201327, Argentina's largest win ever over Wales. The national squad next hosted the world's top team, the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]]. The New Zealanders survived an Argentine assault in the final minutes to hang on to win 25\u201319 and to deny Argentina a huge upset.\n\n''Los Pumas'' began their final preparation for the [[2007 Rugby World Cup|2007 World Cup]] with a summer two-test series against visiting [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], including a 16\u20130 win at V\u00e9lez Sarsfield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/irish/6715723.stm |title=Argentina 16\u20130 Ireland |publisher=BBC |date=2 June 2007 |accessdate=2 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070705040756/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/irish/6715723.stm| archivedate= 5 July 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"width:80%\"\n|-\n! Argentina national rugby union team matches  \n|-\n|{{Rugbybox |report= \n|referee=\n|date=31 May 1986\n|home={{ru-rt|ARG}}\n|score=15 - 13\n|away={{Ru|FRA}}\n|stadium = }}\n|-\n|{{Rugbybox |report= \n|referee=\n|date=7 June 1986\n|home={{ru-rt|ARG}}\n|score=9 - 22\n|away={{Ru|FRA}}\n|stadium = }}\n|-\n|{{Rugbybox |report= \n|referee= (Owen Doyle {{flagicon|IRE}})\n|date=18 June 1988\n|home={{ru-rt|ARG}}\n|score=15 - 18\n|aw