{"title_page": "Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa", "text_new": "{{Infobox food\n| name             = Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa\n| image            = Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Cup of bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Sweden]]\n| creator          = \n| type             = [[Soup]]\n| served           = Cold or Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Bilberries]], [[sugar]], there is a fact  that you cannot be fat off blueberry soup and you can\u2019t get corona virus [[water]], [[potato starch]]\n}}\n'''Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa''' or '''blueberry soup''' ({{lang-fi|mustikkakeitto}}) is a Scandinavian soup made from [[bilberry|bilberries]], which can be served cold or hot. It is sweet and contains [[starch]], which gives it a fairly thick consistency. It is served either as soup, often together with porridge, or as a drink.\n\nIn the [[United States|USA]], bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa is imported and sold under the trade name ''Bl\u00e5b\u00e4r''. Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa can be home-made from bilberries, sugar, water and [[potato starch]],<ref>[http://www.vasaloparen.se/food_article.jsp?d_id=485 Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa recipe] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050326234650/http://www.vasaloparen.se/food_article.jsp?d_id=485 |date=March 26, 2005 }} {{in lang|sv}}</ref> or it can be bought ready-made or in powdered form, to mix with water.\n\nThe Swedish word for bilberry, ''bl\u00e5b\u00e4r'', literally means \"blueberry\", but the beverage is not made from the North American [[blueberry]] (section ''Cyanococcus'' of the genus ''Vaccinium''), but from the related but distinct [[bilberry]], ''Vaccinium myrtillus'', which grows in the wild throughout Scandinavia and other parts of Europe.\n\n==Uses==\nBl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa is traditionally served to the participants at the ski marathon [[Vasaloppet]], as it is rich in energy. Bilberries have traditionally been used to combat mild [[gastrointestinal ailment]]s,<ref>[http://www.rxlist.com/cgi/alt/bilberry_faq.htm Bilberry] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331024644/http://www.rxlist.com/cgi/alt/bilberry_faq.htm# |date=2008-03-31 }} information from RxList Inc.</ref> and in Sweden and Finland, bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa is often considered suitable food for people with stomach upsets, also because it is energy-rich.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kissel]], similar dish in Eastern Slav and Baltic cuisines\n*\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Blueberries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blabarssoppa}}\n[[Category:Swedish soups]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Fruit soups]]\n[[Category:Cross-country skiing in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Blueberries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox food\n| name             = Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa\n| image            = Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Cup of bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Sweden]]\n| creator          = \n| type             = [[Soup]]\n| served           = Cold or Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Bilberries]], [[sugar]], [[water]], [[potato starch]]\n}}\n'''Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa''' or '''blueberry soup''' ({{lang-fi|mustikkakeitto}}) is a Scandinavian soup made from [[bilberry|bilberries]], which can be served cold or hot. It is sweet and contains [[starch]], which gives it a fairly thick consistency. It is served either as soup, often together with porridge, or as a drink.\n\nIn the [[United States|USA]], bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa is imported and sold under the trade name ''Bl\u00e5b\u00e4r''. Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa can be home-made from bilberries, sugar, water and [[potato starch]],<ref>[http://www.vasaloparen.se/food_article.jsp?d_id=485 Bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa recipe] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050326234650/http://www.vasaloparen.se/food_article.jsp?d_id=485 |date=March 26, 2005 }} {{in lang|sv}}</ref> or it can be bought ready-made or in powdered form, to mix with water.\n\nThe Swedish word for bilberry, ''bl\u00e5b\u00e4r'', literally means \"blueberry\", but the beverage is not made from the North American [[blueberry]] (section ''Cyanococcus'' of the genus ''Vaccinium''), but from the related but distinct [[bilberry]], ''Vaccinium myrtillus'', which grows in the wild throughout Scandinavia and other parts of Europe.\n\n==Uses==\nBl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa is traditionally served to the participants at the ski marathon [[Vasaloppet]], as it is rich in energy. Bilberries have traditionally been used to combat mild [[gastrointestinal ailment]]s,<ref>[http://www.rxlist.com/cgi/alt/bilberry_faq.htm Bilberry] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331024644/http://www.rxlist.com/cgi/alt/bilberry_faq.htm# |date=2008-03-31 }} information from RxList Inc.</ref> and in Sweden and Finland, bl\u00e5b\u00e4rssoppa is often considered suitable food for people with stomach upsets, also because it is energy-rich.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kissel]], similar dish in Eastern Slav and Baltic cuisines\n*\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Blueberries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blabarssoppa}}\n[[Category:Swedish soups]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Fruit soups]]\n[[Category:Cross-country skiing in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Blueberries]]\n", "name_user": "185.57.87.43", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bl%C3%A5b%C3%A4rssoppa"}
{"title_page": "Naismith College Coach of the Year", "text_new": "{{infobox sports award\n| name = Naismith College Coach of the Year\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| description = the most outstanding men's and women's basketball head coaches in [[NCAA Division I]]\n| presenter = Atlanta Tipoff Club\n| country = \n| location = \n| year = 1987\n| holder = [[Anthony Grant]], [[2019\u201320 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]] (men)<br>[[Dawn Staley]], [[2019\u201320 South Carolina Gamecocks women's basketball team|South Carolina]] (women)\n| website = \n}}\n'''Naismith College Coach of the Year Award''' is an [[award]] given by the Atlanta Tipoff Club to one men's and one women's [[NCAA Division I]] collegiate coach each season since 1987. The award was originally given to the two winning coaches of the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Division I basketball tournament]] for the first two years of its existence; in 1989, the Naismith Award's governing board decided to give it out via voting process.\n\n==Key==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFFF99; border:1px solid #aaaaaa; width:6em\"| *\n|Denotes coaches [[List of coaches in the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|inducted]] to the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]]\n|-\n|Coach (#)\n|Denotes the number of times the coach has won the award at that point\n|-\n|}\n\n==Winners==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n| align = right\n| image1 =\n| width1 = 200\n| caption1 = [[Steve Fisher]] of [[San Diego State Aztecs men's basketball|San Diego State]] won the 2011 men's award.\n| image2 = Pat-Summitt-Walter-Reed-Center-06-24-08-2.jpg\n| width2 = 116\n| caption2 = [[Pat Summitt]] of [[Tennessee Lady Volunteers basketball|Tennessee]] holds more awards (5) than any other female coach.\n| image3 = Geno-Auriemma-UConn-vs-Texas-3-23-08.jpg\n| width3 = 176\n| caption3 = [[Geno Auriemma]] of [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]] has won the award a record eight times.\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Men's Coach\n!College\n!Women's Coach\n!College\n|-\n|[[1986\u201387 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1986\u201387]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Bob|Knight}}*\n|[[1986\u201387 Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball team|Indiana]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Pat|Summitt}}*\n|[[Tennessee Lady Volunteers basketball|Tennessee]]\n|-\n|[[1987\u201388 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1987\u201388]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Larry|Brown|dab=basketball}}*\n|[[1987\u201388 Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball team|Kansas]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Leon|Barmore}}*\n|[[Louisiana Tech Lady Techsters basketball|Louisiana Tech]]\n|-\n|[[1988\u201389 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1988\u201389]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Mike|Krzyzewski}}*\n|[[1988\u201389 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Pat|Summitt}}* (2)\n|[[Tennessee Lady Volunteers basketball|Tennessee]]\n|-\n|[[1989\u201390 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1989\u201390]]\n|{{sortname|Bobby|Cremins}}\n|[[1989\u201390 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball team|Georgia Tech]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Tara|VanDerveer}}*\n|[[Stanford Cardinal women's basketball|Stanford]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1990\u201391]]\n|{{sortname|Randy|Ayers}}\n|[[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|Ohio State]]\n|{{sortname|Debbie|Ryan}}\n|[[Virginia Cavaliers women's basketball|Virginia]]\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1991\u201392]]\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\" |{{sortname|Mike|Krzyzewski}}* (2)\n|[[1991\u201392 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]]\n|{{sortname|Chris|Weller}}\n|[[Maryland Terrapins women's basketball|Maryla